===Etymology1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|snape|snape|to nip, injure, afflict; cold, nipping; to rebuke, revile, criticize|lang=enm}}, also ''snaipen'', from {{etyl|non}} {{term|snepya||to outrage, dishonor, disgrace}}

===Verb===
# (Shipbuilding) To bevel the end of a timber to fit against an inclined surface.
# {{obsolete}} to [[nip]], [[injure]], [[afflict]]
#: ''Þe snawe snitered ful snart, þat '''snayped''' þe wylde.'' &mdash; ''Sir Gawain and the Green Knight''
# {{obsolete}} to be hard upon, [[rebuke]], [[snub]], [[criticize]]
#: ''Vte of desert þar he was in, He com to '''snaip''' þe king sinn.'' &mdash; ''Cursor Mundi''

===Etymology2===
First attested in the late 18th century.  Derived from various villages in England and southern Scotland sharing this name.

